  "prompt": "Can a Greek question mark (;) be used instead of a semicolon (;) in a programming language such as C#, Java or Pascal?",
  "response": "No, a Greek question mark (;) cannot be used interchangeably with a semicolon (;) in programming languages like C#, Java, or Pascal.\n\nWhile they may visually resemble each other, they are distinct characters with different Unicode values:\n\n- The **semicolon (;)** used in programming languages has a Unicode value of U+003B.\n- The **Greek question mark (;)** has a Unicode value of U+037E.\n\nProgramming languages like C#, Java, and Pascal are designed to recognize only the standard semicolon (;) as a statement terminator or delimiter. Using the Greek question mark instead will result in a syntax error because the compiler or interpreter does not recognize it as a valid character for that purpose.\n\nAlways ensure you use the correct semicolon character when writing code in programming languages.",
